{"type":"message","id":"90f743ed","parentId":"7bf803df","timestamp":"2026-04-13T05:17:59.602Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now `!.env.production` is after `.env*`, so it should NOT be ignored (since `!` negates). The output says `.gitignore:35:!.env.production .env.production` - which means git is showing the pattern that matches, and `.env.production` matches the pattern `!.env.production` (un-ignore pattern). Wait, `git check-ignore -v` shows the pattern that causes the file to be ignored. If the file is NOT ignored, it returns nothing.\n\nActually, looking at the output again:\n```\n.gitignore:35:!.env.production\t.env.production\n\n\n```\n\nThe format is `<file>:<line>:<pattern><TAB><filename` which means the pattern `!.env.production` at line 35 matches `.env.production`. But this pattern is a NEGATION pattern (starts with `!`), which means it would UN-ignore the file, not ignore it. Git's `check-ignore -v` output can be confusing for negation patterns - when a file matches a negation pattern, it's considered NOT ignored. The real test is whether the file shows up in `git status` when staged.\n\nLet me verify this by actually trying to add the file to git.\n```","thinkingSignature":"ffa6e5c822d0c46fd8dd0907c98e0031b9a3866bf0f2671698dd38d515e78500"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vz2kmv8delz0_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw/workspaces/teacher-driving-training-system.bootstrap-backup/ahv-qlhv-fe && git add .env.production .gitignore && git status"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":165,"output":320,"cacheRead":107832,"cacheWrite":506,"totalTokens":108823,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776057468282,"responseId":"062baf7ef0462c01126e7f60fd491727"}}
